Task 1¶

Read Chapter 1-3 of Fundamentals of Data Visualizations, then answer the questions below.

Question 1.1¶

Describe the visualisation concept scales.

Answer 1.1¶

A scale defines a unique mapping between data and aesthetics, and a scale must be one-to-one, such that for each specific data value there is exactly one aesthetics value and vice versa.

Question 1.2¶

In Figures 2.3 and 2.4, the same data is visualised in two different ways. Discuss the pros and cons of the two approaches. Which one do you prefer and why?

Answer 1.2¶

For Figure 2.3, it's easy to observe the trend as the months change from January to December, and its also easier to identify the exact value for any particular month.

For Figure 2.4, it uses colors to clearly show the differences in values, making it more intuitive. However, this method doesn't allow us to confirm the exact value for a specific month, as it's difficult to correlate the color with the exact temperature.

Personally, I prefer Figure 2.4 because I think it is more beautiful and intuitive. Additionally, Figure 2.4 avoids the issue of line overlap, which may occur in Figure 2.3.

Question 1.3¶

Describe situations when nonlinear axes might be useful. When should they not be used?

Answer 1.3¶

When the data range varies significantly, we may use nonlinear axes. For ratio data, we might use a logarithmic scale, and for exponential data, we might use an exponential scale.

When the dataset contains negative or zero values, we cannot use a logarithmic scale, as it would be meaningless. When the data changes uniformly, it's better to use linear axes to better express the data's information. If the dataset has extreme values, nonlinear axes may overemphasize these extreme points.

Question 1.4¶

In which situations could a polar coordinate system be useful?

Answer 1.4¶

Polar coordinates can be useful for data of a periodic nature, such that data values at one end of the scale can be logically joined to data values at the other end.

from pandas.api.types import CategoricalDtype

data = pd.read_csv("Weather_not_tidy.csv")
tidy_data = pd.melt(data,
                    id_vars=['month', 'day', 'hour_of_day'], 
                    value_vars=['Temp2009', 'Temp2010'],
                    var_name='year', 
                    value_name='temperature')

tidy_data['year'] = tidy_data['year'].str.replace('Temp', '').astype(int)

month_order = CategoricalDtype(['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 
                                'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'], ordered=True)
tidy_data['month'] = tidy_data['month'].astype(month_order)

tidy_data = tidy_data.sort_values(by=['year', 'month', 'day']).reset_index(drop=True)
tidy_data = tidy_data[['year', 'month', 'day', 'hour_of_day', 'temperature']]

# Group data by month and year to calculate mean and standard deviation
mean_temperature = tidy_data.groupby(['month', 'year'])['temperature'].mean().reset_index()
std_temperature = tidy_data.groupby(['month', 'year'])['temperature'].std().reset_index()

# Merge the dataframes to get both mean and standard deviation
temperature_error_data = pd.merge(mean_temperature, std_temperature, on=['month', 'year'], suffixes=('_mean', '_std'))

# Create the plot with error bars
error_bar_plot = (
    ggplot(temperature_error_data, aes(x='month', y='temperature_mean', fill='factor(year)', color='factor(year)')) 
    + geom_errorbar(
        aes(ymin='temperature_mean - temperature_std', ymax='temperature_mean + temperature_std'), 
        width=0.2,
        position=position_dodge(0.5)  # Dodge for separation between years
    )
    + geom_point(size=2, position=position_dodge(0.5))  # Add points with dodge to align
    + labs(
        title='Error Bars for Temperature)', 
        x='Month', 
        y='Temperature (C)'
    )
)

Briefly discuss the drawback with each approach (standard errors, boxplots, and violin plots).

Write answer here

Standard errors plot can't show the data distribution, which can be misleading. Boxplots summarize the distribution but don't reveal detailed shapes. Violin plots show density but it could be difficult to interpret with sparse or skewed data.

One of the drawbacks with a violin plot is that it can be hard to read summary statistics from it. Produce a violin plot visual here, where you have also drawn the median for each violin, as well as the data points.

In [11]:
violin_plot = (
    ggplot(tidy_data, aes(x='month', y='temperature', fill='factor(year)'))
    + geom_violin(position='dodge', alpha=0.7)  # Add violin plots
    + scale_fill_manual(values=cbPalette[:2], labels=['2009', '2010'])  # Set colors for the years
    + geom_jitter(size=2, alpha=0.6, position=position_dodge(0.7))  # Add jittered dots for individual data points
    + stat_summary(
        fun_y=np.median,  # Use median for summary statistic
        fun_ymin=np.median,  # ymin is also the median
        fun_ymax=np.median,  # ymax is also the median
        geom='errorbar',  # Use errorbars to indicate the median line
        color='black',  # Color for the median line
        width=0.5,  # Width of the error bar
        position=position_dodge(0.7)  # Dodge to avoid overlap
    )
    + labs(
        title='Violin Plot for Temperature',
        x='Month',
        y='Temperature (C)',
        fill='Year'
    )
    + theme_minimal()  # Use minimal theme
    + annotate(
        'text', x=2, y=max(tidy_data['temperature']) + 1,
        label='Black line: Median', color='black', size=10, ha='center'
    )  # Add a custom annotation for the median
)

violin_plot

Briefly discuss how you could make it easy for the reader to understand that the line the visual represent the median.

I added an annotation labeling the black line as the median, making it clear and easy for readers to understand its purpose in the visual.

Some people argue that visuals should be as minimal as possible. On the webpage you have a bad example of a minimalist way to plot the min, median, and max temperature of each month in 2009 and 2010 using the dataset in Question 3.2 (where you hopefully have filtered out daily temperatures for 2009 and 2010). By only using geom_point recreate the visual (you do not need to recreate the title). You are not allowed to transform the dataset.

Hint - Remember the stat argument in ggplot

In [12]:
# Insert code here 
from plotnine import scale_x_discrete

# Define the order of months
months = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec']

# Create the plot with min, median, and max temperatures
plot = (ggplot(tidy_data, aes(x='month', y='temperature', color='factor(year)'))  # Group by year
        + stat_summary(fun_y=np.median, geom='point', size=2, shape='s')  # Median points
        + stat_summary(fun_y=np.min, geom='point', size=2, shape='o')  # Min points
        + stat_summary(fun_y=np.max, geom='point', size=2, shape='x')  # Max points
        + scale_x_discrete(limits=months)  # Set the month order
        + labs(x='Month', y='Temperature [C]', color='Year')  # Labels for axes
        + theme_minimal()  # Minimal theme
)

# Display the plot

# Load the dataset
data = pd.read_csv('Weather_tidy_full.csv')

# Filter data for 2008 January
data_2008_jan = data[(data['year'] == 2008) & (data['month'] == 'Jan')]

# Select only the noon (12:00) and evening (18:00) temperature data
day_data = data_2008_jan[data_2008_jan['hour_of_day'] == 12]
night_data = data_2008_jan[data_2008_jan['hour_of_day'] == 18]

# Create a new DataFrame with the time of day and corresponding temperatures
day_night_data = pd.concat([day_data[['day', 'Temperature']].assign(time_of_day='Noon'),
                            night_data[['day', 'Temperature']].assign(time_of_day='Evening')])

# Create the line plot comparing daytime and nighttime temperatures for January 2008
plot_day_night_comparison = (
    ggplot(day_night_data, aes(x='day', y='Temperature', color='time_of_day'))
    + geom_line(size=1.2)
    + labs(x='Day of January 2008', y='Temperature [C]', title='Day vs Night Temperature Comparison (Jan 2008)')
    + theme(axis_text_x=element_text(angle=45, hjust=1))  # Rotate x-axis labels for better visibility
)

# Display the plot
plot_day_night_comparison

Brief motivation

A line plot is used to compare daytime and nighttime temperatures, clearly showing the daily temperature fluctuations and the difference between day and night in January 2008.

# Insert code here for Fig. 6.2
# Sort the data by 'gross' in ascending order
data = data.sort_values(by=['gross'])

# Define and reverse the titles for the x-axis labels
titles = ['Star Wars', 'Jumanji', 'Pitch Perfect 3', 'Greatest Showman', 'Ferdinand']
titles.reverse()

# Create the bar plot
plot = (
    ggplot(data, aes(x='Title', y='gross / 1000000'))  # Plot gross in millions
    + geom_bar(position='dodge', stat='identity', fill='cyan', alpha=0.6, width=0.8)  # Bars with custom width and transparency
    + scale_x_discrete(limits=data['Title'], labels=titles)  # Ensure correct order and labels for titles
    + scale_y_continuous(breaks=[0, 20, 40, 60])  # Show only 0, 20, 40, 60 on y-axis
    + ylab('Weekend gross (million USD)')  # Add y-axis label
    + xlab('')  # Remove x-axis label
    + coord_flip()  # Flip the coordinates for horizontal bars
    + theme_minimal()  # Use a minimal theme
    + theme(
        panel_grid_major_y=element_blank(),  # Remove horizontal grid lines
        panel_grid_minor_y=element_blank(),  # Remove minor grid lines
        panel_grid_minor_x=element_blank(),  # Remove all minor x grid lines
        panel_grid_major_x=element_line(color="gray", size=0.5),  # Show only major x grid lines (0, 20, 40, 60)
        axis_line=element_blank()  # Remove all axis lines
    )
)

Often we want to highlight a specific column in a barplot. Using the same layout as in the most recent plot highlight the column of Jumanji in orange, and keep the remaining columns grey.

In [17]:
# Insert code here 
# Sort the data by 'gross' in ascending order
data = data.sort_values(by=['gross'])

# Define and reverse the titles for the x-axis labels
titles = ['Star Wars', 'Jumanji', 'Pitch Perfect 3', 'Greatest Showman', 'Ferdinand']
titles.reverse()

# Create a new column for fill color
data['fill_color'] = ['orange' if title == 'Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle' else 'grey' for title in data['Title']]

# Create the bar plot
plot = (
    ggplot(data, aes(x='Title', y='gross / 1000000', fill='fill_color'))  # Map fill color based on the condition
    + geom_bar(position='dodge', stat='identity', alpha=0.6, width=0.8)  # Bars with custom width and transparency
    + scale_fill_identity()  # Use the exact fill colors defined in the data
    + scale_x_discrete(limits=data['Title'], labels=titles)  # Ensure correct order and labels for titles
    + scale_y_continuous(breaks=[0, 20, 40, 60])  # Show only 0, 20, 40, 60 on y-axis
    + ylab('Weekend gross (million USD)')  # Add y-axis label
    + xlab('')  # Remove x-axis label
    + coord_flip()  # Flip the coordinates for horizontal bars
    + theme_minimal()  # Use a minimal theme
    + theme(
        panel_grid_major_y=element_blank(),  # Remove horizontal grid lines
        panel_grid_minor_y=element_blank(),  # Remove minor grid lines
        panel_grid_minor_x=element_blank(),  # Remove all minor x grid lines
        panel_grid_major_x=element_line(color="gray", size=0.5),  # Show only major x grid lines (0, 20, 40, 60)
        axis_line=element_blank()  # Remove all axis lines
    )
    + theme(legend_position='none')
)

# Add the numeric labels for the highlighted category (Jumanji)
# Sort the data by 'gross' in ascending order
data = data.sort_values(by=['gross'])

# Define and reverse the titles for the x-axis labels
titles = ['Star Wars', 'Jumanji', 'Pitch Perfect 3', 'Greatest Showman', 'Ferdinand']
titles.reverse()

# Create a new column for fill color
data['fill_color'] = ['orange' if title == 'Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle' else 'grey' for title in data['Title']]

# Create a new column for labels with the rounded 'gross' value
data['label'] = data['gross'] / 1000000  # In million USD

# Create the bar plot
plot = (
    ggplot(data, aes(x='Title', y='gross / 1000000', fill='fill_color'))  # Map fill color based on the condition
    + geom_bar(position='dodge', stat='identity', alpha=0.6, width=0.8)  # Bars with custom width and transparency
    + scale_fill_identity()  # Use the exact fill colors defined in the data
    + scale_x_discrete(limits=data['Title'], labels=titles)  # Ensure correct order and labels for titles
    + scale_y_continuous(breaks=[0, 20, 40, 60])  # Show only 0, 20, 40, 60 on y-axis
    + ylab('weekend gross (million USD)')  # Add y-axis label
    + xlab('')  # Remove x-axis label
    + coord_flip()  # Flip the coordinates for horizontal bars
    + theme_minimal()  # Use a minimal theme
    + theme(
        panel_grid_major_y=element_blank(),  # Remove horizontal grid lines
        panel_grid_minor_y=element_blank(),  # Remove minor grid lines
        panel_grid_minor_x=element_blank(),  # Remove all minor x grid lines
        panel_grid_major_x=element_line(color="gray", size=0.5),  # Show only major x grid lines (0, 20, 40, 60)
        axis_line=element_blank()  # Remove all axis lines
    )
    + theme(legend_position='none')  # Hide the legend
)

# Add the numeric labels for the highlighted category (Jumanji)
plot = plot + geom_text(
    data=data[data['Title'] == 'Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle'],  # Filter to highlight only Jumanji
    mapping=aes(x='Title', y='gross / 1000000', label=round(data[data['Title'] == 'Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle']['label'].values[0], 1)),  # Use the value for Jumanji only
    nudge_y=-18,  # Adjust the text position slightly above the bar
    color='black',  # Text color
    size=9  # Text size
)

Question 4.3¶

On the webpage, I have uploaded a dataset on the number of marriages in Stockholm, Gothenburg, Malmo and rest of Sweden for 2020, 2015, 2010 and 2005. Using this dataset, produce i) a visual where it is easy to see which year Stockholm had the second most marriages, and ii) a visual where it is easy to see how many more marriages there was in Stockholm compared to Gothenburg in 2015. In each visual, I want you to include the number of marriages for each city and year.

In [19]:
# Insert code here for part i)
# Load the dataset
df = pd.read_csv('Marriage.csv')

# Ensure categorical columns are set correctly
df['region'] = pd.Categorical(df['region'])
df['year'] = pd.Categorical(df['year'])

# Define color palette
color_palette = ['#aae4f3', '#55c8e7', '#007eff', '#00468e']

# Define the order and names for the regions and years
regions_order = ['Rest_of_sweden', 'Stockholm', 'Gothenburg', 'Malmo']
regions_names = ['Rest of Sweden', 'Stockholm', 'Gothenburg', 'Malmo']

# Reverse region order for plot
regions_names.reverse()
regions_order.reverse()

# Set region as a categorical variable with specific order
df['region_cat'] = pd.Categorical(df['region'], categories=regions_order)

# Define the year categories and reverse for plotting
year_categories = [2005, 2010, 2015, 2020]
year_categories.reverse()

# Set year as a categorical variable with specific order
df['year_cat'] = pd.Categorical(df['year'], categories=year_categories)

# Sort values by year to maintain chronological order in the plot
df = df.sort_values('year_cat')

# Create the bar plot with number labels
plot = (
    ggplot(df, aes(x='region_cat', y='number_marriges', fill='year'))  # Mapping the variables to axes and color
    + geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', alpha=0.7)  # Bar chart with dodged bars
    + labs(y='Number of Marriages', x='Region', title='Number of Marriages by Region and Year in Sweden')  # Titles and axis labels
    + scale_fill_manual(values=color_palette, name='Year')  # Manual fill colors for each year
    + scale_x_discrete(limits=regions_order, labels=regions_names)  # Ensure correct region order and labels
    + coord_flip()  # Flip coordinates for horizontal bars
    + theme_minimal()  # Apply minimal theme for clean design
)

# Display the plot
plot

    + geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', alpha=0.7)  # Bar chart with dodged bars for each year, grouped by region
    + labs(x='Year', y='Number of Marriages', title='Number of Marriages by Year and Region in Sweden')  # Titles and axis labels
    + scale_fill_manual(values=color_palette, name='Region', labels=regions_names)  # Manual fill colors for regions
    + scale_x_discrete(limits=year_categories, labels=[str(year) for year in year_categories])  # Set the correct order and labels for years
    + scale_y_continuous(labels=lambda l: [f'{int(x)}' for x in l], limits=(0, df['number_marriges'].max() + 500))  # Display number labels for y-axis
    + coord_flip()  # Flip the coordinates to make the chart horizontal (years on y-axis, regions on x-axis)
    + theme_minimal()  # Apply minimal theme for clean design
)

# Display the plot
plot

# Remember to print the visual

Question 4.4¶

When plotting the mobile operating system data in the lectures, I used a classical barplot. Another way which makes it easy to track the trend over several years or across companies is a common line-plot. Using the dataset on the webpage recreate the present on the webpage.

In [21]:
# Insert code here
# Load the mobile OS market share data
os_market_data = pd.read_csv('mobile_os_market_share.csv')

# Filter the data for the years 2009, 2010, and 2011
filtered_os_data = os_market_data.query('Year == 2009 or Year == 2010 or Year == 2011')

# Define the order of operating systems
os_order = ["iOS", "BlackBerry OS", "Android", "Unknown", "Other", "Playstation", "SymbianOS", "Windows"]

# Assign the operating system as a categorical variable to ensure the correct ordering
filtered_os_data = filtered_os_data.assign(OperatingSystem=pd.Categorical(filtered_os_data["OperatingSystem"], 
                                                                         categories=os_order))

# Create the plot using ggplot
os_line_plot = (
    ggplot(filtered_os_data, aes(x='Year', y='Share', color='OperatingSystem'))  # Set axes and color by OS
    + geom_line(size=1)  # Add line plot with a line width of 1
    + geom_point(size=2)  # Add points to the plot
    + scale_x_continuous(breaks=[2009, 2010, 2011])  # Specify x-axis ticks for the years
    + scale_color_manual(values=cbPalette)  # Set custom color palette for the operating systems
    + labs(y='Market Share (%)', x='Year')  # Add axis labels
    + theme_minimal()  # Use minimal theme
    + guides(color=guide_legend(title='Operating System', nrow=2))  # Customize legend
    + theme(figure_size=(8, 6), legend_position='bottom')  # Place the legend at the bottom
)

# Display the plot
os_line_plot
# Remember to print the visual

By default plotnine places the legend for a visual to the right, or bottom depending on a theme. Do you think having a legend next to the visual is the best solution?

No, placing the legend next to the visual isn't always ideal, especially with many items. It can crowd the plot. Placing it below may provide more space and improve readability.

# Insert code here for part2 
# Read the CSV file into a DataFrame
data = pd.read_csv('Life_tidy_full.csv')

# Select the countries of interest
countries_of_interest = ['South Korea', 'China', 'Japan', 'Vietnam', 'India', 'Philippines', 'Malaysia']

# Filter the data for the selected countries and the year 2020
filtered_data_2020 = data[(data['country'].isin(countries_of_interest)) & (data['Year'] == 2020)]

# Sort the data by 'Life_expactancy' in descending order
filtered_data_2020 = filtered_data_2020.sort_values(by='Life_expactancy', ascending=False)

# Update the country column to maintain the sorted order in the plot
filtered_data_2020['country'] = pd.Categorical(filtered_data_2020['country'], 
                                               categories=filtered_data_2020['country'], 
                                               ordered=True)

# Define a color palette to avoid automatic scale issues
color_palette = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728', '#9467bd', '#8c564b', '#e377c2']

# Create a scatter plot
plot = (ggplot(filtered_data_2020) 
        + aes(x='country', y='Life_expactancy', color='country')  # x-axis: 'country', y-axis: 'Life_expactancy'
        + geom_point(size=4)  # Scatter points size
        + scale_color_manual(values=color_palette)  # Explicitly set color palette
        + labs(title='Life Expectancy of Selected Countries in 2020',  # Title of the plot
               x='Country', y='Life Expectancy')  # Labels for the x and y axes
        + theme_minimal())

# Display the plot
plot
# Remember to print the visual

Brief motivation

The scatter plot is chosen to clearly compare life expectancy across countries, highlighting differences in 2020 values with distinct data points for each country.
